==============================================================================
Vendored agent guidance (.agents/skills/)
==============================================================================

This directory contains Rust coding-guidance "skills" consumed by AI coding
agents. Full provenance and the conflict decisions between the sources are
documented in .agents/skills/readme.md.

* .agents/skills/rust-skills/
    The "rust-skills" rule pack from leonardomso/rust-skills
    (https://github.com/leonardomso/rust-skills), vendored at commit
    89910e8585331dabbecd400ae132b4070ecf24af.
    Copyright (c) 2025 Leonardo Maldonado.
    Licensed under the MIT License. The full upstream license text is
    preserved in-tree at .agents/skills/rust-skills/LICENSE and must be
    retained in any copy or substantial portion of that directory.

* .agents/skills/rust100k-architecture-docs/
  .agents/skills/rust100k-build-performance/
  .agents/skills/rust100k-testing-discipline/
    Original guidance text under this repository's MIT License, derived from
    the ideas in Alex Kladov's ("matklad") "Rust100k" article series
    (https://matklad.github.io/2021/09/05/Rust100k.html).

* .agents/skills/parse-dont-validate/
  .agents/skills/names-are-not-type-safety/
    Original guidance text under this repository's MIT License, derived from
    the ideas in Alexis King's articles "Parse, don't validate"
    (https://lexi-lambda.github.io/blog/2019/11/05/parse-don-t-validate/) and
    "Names are not type safety"
    (https://lexi-lambda.github.io/blog/2020/11/01/names-are-not-type-safety/).

==============================================================================
Third-party dependencies
==============================================================================

`eph` depends on third-party Rust crates declared in Cargo.toml and pinned in
Cargo.lock, including (non-exhaustively) anyhow, bollard, clap, dirs,
futures-util, hex, serde, serde_json, sha2, shell-words, tokio, tracing, and
tracing-subscriber. Each remains under its own license (predominantly MIT
and/or Apache-2.0). Their license texts are distributed with the respective
crates via crates.io; run `cargo license` or `cargo about generate` to produce
a complete dependency license report.
